post_text:
#FACS HS robotics team, the Bots of Prey, overcame adversity at their competition. They were faced with numerous setbacks throughout the day which forced them to dynamically evaluate and respond with alternative solutions to the challenges. Yet they persevered through the early rounds gaining experience and using the robot's innovative capabilities that hadn't been available earlier in the day. The final rounds of the competition were both stressful and engaging.

In order to qualify for states, the Bots of Prey had to either win the final match or earn the highest award possible, the Inspire award for the best all around team. Unfortunately, they placed second in the final match, but there was still hope. The team was very nervous during the award ceremony, where they didn‚Äôt receive any awards until the very end... the moment we‚Äôve all been waiting for... 1st place Inspire goes to the Bots of Prey!!!

Congrats to the team for all their hard work and resilience!

post_text: #FACS Science Lab: A Spine Model. Students used Twizzler strands (spinal cord/nerves), hard Life Savers (vertebrae), and Gummy Life Savers (inter-vertebral disks/cartilage) to represent the parts of a spine. Students built, observed, and discussed a spine with only vertebrae and only inter-vertebral disks/cartilage. Students then built correct spines with alternating vertebrae and inter-vertebral disks. Students noticed the structure and protection offered by our hard Life Savers as well as the cushion and flexibility offered by the gummys.
text: #FACS Science Lab: A Spine Model. Students used Twizzler strands (spinal cord/nerves), hard Life Savers (vertebrae), and Gummy Life Savers (inter-vertebral disks/cartilage) to represent the parts of a spine. Students built, observed, and discussed a spine with only vertebrae and only inter-vertebral disks/cartilage. Students then built correct spines with alternating vertebrae and inter-vertebral disks. Students noticed the structure and protection offered by our hard Life Savers as well as the cushion and flexibility offered by the gummys.

post_text:
Congratulations to Aimee Heroux! Aimee attended the Sister Cities Youth Leadership Summit in Houston, Texas on a scholarship from Sister Cities Raleigh. The summit is designed to bring youth together from all over the world and encourage them to use their talents and interests to solve global issues. She participated in seminars from world leaders, team building activities, and a competition in each of the five tracks: STEM, Entrepreneurship, Film making, Voices of Youth, and Diplomacy. Aimee participated in the diplomacy track in which the competition consisted of attempting to create a feasible resolution on taking action against climate change modeled after the U.N.. After her team won their competition, they had the opportunity to present our resolution in front of the Sister Cities Summit which was geared towards world leaders, diplomats, and politicians.
#FACS

post_text: This was the first time in #FACS history that our school dedicated a day so that students can get interviews, press conference experience, photos and videos for use throughout the season. The media day effort was coordinated and executed by 25 sports media students and led by senior producers Alec Handlin and Matthew Schweikert. This truly was as close to a professional media experience as we can afford to give our students and it was a resounding success.
